                description: "A socio-legal study examining how public parks in urban Karnataka are planned, governed, and accessed \u2014 with recommendations for legal reform, inclusive design, and better accountability.",
                themes: ["Placemaking & Urban Ecology"],
                time: 3, workload: 3, budget: 2,
                whatIsIt: "A Park for All is a socio-legal effort examining how public parks in urban Karnataka, with a focus on Bengaluru, are planned, governed, and accessed in rapidly urbanising cities. It analyses legal and policy frameworks around parks and highlights governance gaps like poor implementation, land diversion, and weak maintenance systems. It also focuses on making parks inclusive for marginalised communities such as gig workers and waste pickers. Developed with MOD Foundation, NOTF, Policy Adda at BIC, and Citizen Matters.",
                whyExists: "Urban parks suffer from inadequate and fragmented governance \u2014 overlapping authorities, weak laws, and poor implementation lead to badly planned, maintained, and protected green spaces. Park land is lost through diversion, encroachment, and lack of accountability. Access is unequal \u2014 parks are not designed or managed to serve marginalised groups in cities.",
                involves: ["Strengthening legal, policy, and governance frameworks for park management", "Clarifying which authorities are responsible for parks and closing policy gaps", "Better planning and data systems including mapping park access and setting green space standards", "Inclusive and participatory design ensuring parks serve diverse users", "Multi-stakeholder dialogues aligning government, civil society, and community actors", "Workshops for citizen groups on legal reform and effective legal design"],
                whereDone: "Research focused on Bengaluru and urban Karnataka. Shared as a resource through Policy Adda at BLR Hubba. Engaging with citizen groups in Bengaluru as a starting point.",
                impact: "Highlighted the need for legal reform and drew attention to gaps in existing frameworks. Shared as a resource by organisations working in urban sustainability. Recognised at Policy Adda as filling a critical knowledge gap in urban park governance.",
                whatsNeeded: "Multi-stakeholder dialogues to align government, civil society, and community actors. Convening practitioners and stakeholders with shared tools and research. Community workshops on legal reform. Continuous feedback loops between communities and decision-makers.",
                links: ["https://vidhilegalpolicy.in/research/a-park-for-all-planning-and-governing-green-for-urban-karnataka/"],
